I. Coding guidelines

a. Main variables of interest

For a cross-country comparison of climate-related attitudes, we combined 2 sets of data:

  1. Global Attitudes Survey: a global survey across 15 countries, excluding the U.S.
  2. American Trends Panel: a national survey of U.S. adults

However, in terms of the geographic scope of our analysis, we examined 6 of the 16 countries for which data was available.

The 6 countries were chosen in such a way so as to reflect geographical representation and the standards against which we selected these countries were as follows:

  • The worlds top 10 biggest polluters: U.S., Germany, South Korea
  • Countries at the forefront of taking climate action: Australia, Sweden, The Netherlands

Specifically, the main variables of interest in our dataset were:

               stargazer, ggeffects, dotwhisker, # for generating regression outputs

# Read in the Global Attitudes Survey
Global_raw <- haven::read_sav("./Dataset/Global Attitudes Survey (Spring 2021).sav")

# Read in the American Trends Panel

III. Data wrangling

a. The Global Attitudes Survey

1) Clean the column names

  • Simplify the variable names of 1) education and 2) income related variables (i.e.D_EDUC_[COUNTRY NAME] and D_INCOME_[COUNTRY NAME])
    • Remove unnecessary strings (i.e.D_ and _2017)
  • Rename EDUC_AUSTRALIA ( = the highest year of primary or secondary school completed; and previously, D_EDUC_AUSTRALIA_2017) as EDUC_AUSTRALIA_SUPPLEMENTARY
    • Append the suffix _SUPPLEMENTARY to indicate that this variable is not the focal measure of educational attainment for analyzing the Australian sample
  • Reassign EDUC_AUSTRALIA_2017B (= the highest level of educational attainment) back to EDUC_AUSTRALIA
    • To indicate that this variable is the main indicator of educational attainment for analyzing the Australian sample

2) Filter the observations by country

  • Subset to respondents from 1) Australia, 2) Germany, 3) Netherlands, 4) South Korea, and 5) Sweden
  • Note:
    The U.S. sample is later to be added to the data set, once the American Trends Panel has been cleaned.

3) Assign country names/nationality to each observation

Global.df <- Global_raw

# Remove 1) prefixes 'D_' and 2) suffixes '_2017'
names(Global.df) <- str_remove_all(names(Global_raw), "^D_|_2017$")
# But keep the suffix '_2017B' as is,
# so that we can work with 'EDUC_AUSTRALIA_2017B' at the very next step of data processing


# Give a descriptive label that distinguishes between the
# 1) focal and 2) supplementary measures of educational attainment 
Global.df <- Global.df %>%
  rename("EDUC_AUSTRALIA_SUPPLEMENTARY" = "EDUC_AUSTRALIA",
         "EDUC_AUSTRALIA" = "EDUC_AUSTRALIA_2017B") %>%
# Subset to respondents from
# Australia, Germany, Netherlands, South Korea, and Sweden, respectively:
  filter(public == 1 | public == 5 | public == 9 | public == 12 | public == 14) %>%
# Instead of displaying numeric values for each national sample,
# assign their descriptive value labels, to indicate respondents' nationality - in strings:
  mutate(COUNTRY = get_labels(public)[public])

4) Standardize the education-related variables

  • The response categories and assigned labels in the original data set reflected cross-country differences in the national education system/structure/curriculum
  • Thus the 1) range of values that the education variables can take on and 2) what each of their response items corresponds to differed substantially by country
  • To be able to make comparisons across countries, we needed to transform the education variables according to consistent standards, before we could go ahead with any data analysis/exploration

Guidelines for recoding education-related variables:

Australia Germany The Netherlands South Korea Sweden
To be recoded as 0 1 - 4 1 - 4 1 - 7 1 - 7 1 - 7
To be recoded as 1 5 - 7 5 - 7 8 - 10 8 - 10 8 - 10
To be recoded as NA 98, 99 8, 9 98, 99 98, 99 98, 99
  • To streamline the recoding of education variables, apply the same function over 1) the Netherlands, 2) South Korea, and 3) Sweden, as these 3 countries follow the same coding scheme
  • Note:
    NA values for Germany are 8 and 9, NOT 98, and 99.
# Define a custom function for cleaning up the education-related variables for
# 1) the Dutch, 2) Korean, and 3) the Swede samples:

clean_response1 <- function(x) {
  cleaned_NA1 = ifelse(x %in% c(98, 99), NA, # Code 'Don't know' and 'Refused' as NA
                       ifelse(x %in% c(8, 9, 10), 1, # 'BA degrees or higher' as 1
# If the data pertains to the [FOCAL COUNTRY] AND isn't a missing value, code as 0 ('No BA degree')
# Otherwise (i.e. if the data doesn't actually pertain to the [FOCAL COUNTRY]), code as NA.
                              ifelse(!is.na(x), 0, NA)))
  return(cleaned_NA1)
}
  • However, we needed to exercise caution when it came to cleaning the Australian sample:
    • Since the missing values in EDUC_AUSTRALIA (= the highest level of education) could be construed not only as 1) a true missing value (NA) but also as 2) not having obtained an undergraduate degree (0),
    • We had to use EDUC_AUSTRALIA_SUPPLEMENTARY (= the highest year of primary or secondary school completed) as aides, to be able to distinguish between the two categories
    • Then, overwrite the missing values in EDUC_AUSTRALIA

In other words, where EDUC_AUSTRALIA was left blank, respondents fell into either of the two categories:

  • Individuals (to be coded as NA) who had
    a) responded that they did not know or
    b) refused to provide an answer
  • Individuals without an undergraduate degree (to be coded as 0), who
    a) have not had any formal schooling,
    b) have completed only primary school, or
    c) have completed secondary school
The highest degree obtained
(EDUC_AUSTRALIA)		 The highest year of primary or secondary school completed
(EDUC_AUSTRALIA_SUPPLEMENTARY)		 To be coded as
Missing a value Dont know NA
Missing a value Refused NA
Missing a value Year 8 or below (usually 14 years old) 0
Missing a value Year 12 or equivalent (usually 18 years old) 0 
Global_edu_cleaned <- Global.df %>%
  mutate(
# For the Australian sample,
# if the highest year of primary/secondary school completion is 'Don't know' or 'Refused',
# code as NA:
    EDUC_AUSTRALIA_TEMPORARY = ifelse(EDUC_AUSTRALIA_SUPPLEMENTARY %in% c(8, 9), NA,
# If the respondent is *NOT* from Australia, also code them as NA. Otherwise, code as 0:
# (** Please refer to the annotation below, for more detail)
                                      ifelse(COUNTRY != 'Australia', NA, 0)),
# Then, overwrite'EDUC_AUSTRALIA_TEMPORARY' over our measure of 'highest degree obtained',
# *ONLY IF* the latter is missing a value.
# The overwritten values will either be an a) 'NA' or b) '0' (for 'Without a BA degree'):
    EDUC_AUSTRALIA_NEW = ifelse(is.na(EDUC_AUSTRALIA), EDUC_AUSTRALIA_TEMPORARY,
                      ifelse(EDUC_AUSTRALIA %in% c(98, 99), NA, # recode the 'Don't know's and 'Refused's
                             ifelse(EDUC_AUSTRALIA %in% c(5, 6, 7), 1, 0))), # recode non-missing values as 0 or 1s
# Next, clean the 'EDUC_GERMANY' column:
    EDUC_GERMANY_NEW = ifelse(EDUC_GERMANY %in% c(8, 9), NA, # recode the 'Don't know's and 'Refused's
                              ifelse(EDUC_GERMANY %in% c(5, 6, 7), 1, # recode the 'BA or higher's
# For the remaining observations in this column, code as 0 if the data is from a German sample.
# Otherwise, code as NA (because these observations are from non-German samples):
                                     ifelse(!is.na(EDUC_GERMANY), 0, NA))),
# For 1) the Netherlands, 2) Korea, and 3) Sweden,
# apply the customized function, then append '_NEW' to the original column names:
    across(c(EDUC_NETHERLANDS, EDUC_SKOREA, EDUC_SWEDEN), ~ clean_response1(.x), .names = "{col}_NEW")) %>%
# Collapse the recoded responses of all 5 countries into a single variable:
  mutate(
    EDUCATION = ifelse(COUNTRY == 'Australia', EDUC_AUSTRALIA_NEW,
                       ifelse(COUNTRY == 'Germany', EDUC_GERMANY_NEW,
                              ifelse(COUNTRY == 'Netherlands', EDUC_NETHERLANDS_NEW,
                                    ifelse(COUNTRY == 'South Korea', EDUC_SKOREA_NEW, EDUC_SWEDEN_NEW)))))

NOTE:
When we created a new column - EDUC_AUSTRALIA_TEMPORARY (see ** of the R code) - we coded all non-missing observations from the Australian sample into 0, although the 0-coded responses would consist of a mix of

  1. Australians without a BA degree and
  2. Australians who hold at least a BA degree

In our measure of the highest degree obtained (EDUC_AUSTRALIA), Australians with a BA degree were coded any one of the following values:

  • 5 - 7, if they did respond to the survey item
  • 98 or 99, if they failed to provide a response

In other words, none of the Australian respondents with a BA degree were missing an assigned value in EDUC_AUSTRALIA.

So when we wrote over our measure of educational attainment (EDUC_AUSTRALIA), the confounding of Australians with and without a BA degree in EDUC_AUSTRALIA_TEMPORARY was NOT a cause of concern,

  • Because we replaced the values ONLY WHEN EDUC_AUSTRALIA was missing an assigned value.

5) Standardize the income-related variables

  • Transform the missing values as NA
    • Given that all 5 of these countries follow the same coding scheme for processing NA values, apply the same function across these countries
    • Compute the median income category of each national sample
  • Code all non-missing values as either 0 or 1s, assigning the value of
    • 0 if the raw value is lower than, and
    • 1 if it is equal to or greater than the national median

Guidelines for recoding the income-related variables:

Australia Germany The Netherlands South Korea Sweden
To be recoded as 0 1 - 5 1 - 5 1 - 4 1 - 7 1 - 7
To be recoded as 1 6 - 12 6 - 10 5 - 9 8 - 12 8 - 12
To be recoded as NA 98, 99 98, 99 98, 99 98, 99 98, 99 
# First, code the 'Don't know's and 'Refused' as NA,
# because calculating the median income category requires the removal of NAs 

# To do so, define a custom function that converts the missing values of income-related variables:
clean_response2 <- function(x) {
  cleaned_NA2 = ifelse(x %in% c(98, 99), NA, x) # keep the non-missing values as-is
  return(cleaned_NA2)
} 


# Apply the function across all 5 countries:
Global_edu_income_cleaning <- Global_edu_cleaned %>% 
  mutate(
    across(starts_with("INCOME_") & ends_with(c("AUSTRALIA", "GERMANY", "NETHERLANDS", "SKOREA", "SWEDEN")), ~ clean_response2(.x)),
# Collapse the responses of each country into a single variable:
    INCOME_UNSTANDARDIZED = ifelse(COUNTRY == 'Australia', INCOME_AUSTRALIA,
                                   ifelse(COUNTRY == 'Germany', INCOME_GERMANY,
                                          ifelse(COUNTRY == 'Netherlands', INCOME_NETHERLANDS,
                                                 ifelse(COUNTRY == 'South Korea', INCOME_SKOREA, INCOME_SWEDEN)))))


# Next, find the median income category for each country
Global_income_median_UNSTANDARDIZED <- Global_edu_income_cleaning %>% 
  group_by(COUNTRY) %>% 
  dplyr::summarize(median_income = median(INCOME_UNSTANDARDIZED, na.rm = TRUE))

Summary of the median income for each national sample:

# Display a table that summarizes the median:
Global_income_median_UNSTANDARDIZED  %>%

# Lastly, standardize the income variables so that:
# values above or equal to the *country* median (i.e. High income) = 1 and
# values below the *country* median (i.e. Low income) = 0

Global_edu_income_cleaned <- Global_edu_income_cleaning %>% 
  mutate(
    INCOME = ifelse(is.na(INCOME_UNSTANDARDIZED), NA, # Code the missing values
# Specify the higher income category among the Australian & German sample:
                    ifelse((COUNTRY %in% c('Australia', 'Germany') & INCOME_UNSTANDARDIZED >= 6) |
# Higher income category among the Dutch sample:
                           (COUNTRY == 'Netherlands' & INCOME_UNSTANDARDIZED >= 5) | 
# Higher income category among the South Korean sample and the Swedes:
# Then code as 1 if high in income, otherwise code as 0
                           (COUNTRY %in% c('South Korea', 'Sweden') &  INCOME_UNSTANDARDIZED >= 8), 1, 0)))

6) Standardize the responses across the Global and the US data set

  • To perform a logistic regression, convert the dependent variable (CLIMATE_INTLCOMMUNITY) into a binary variable
    • Rename it as CLIMATE_CONFIDENCE
  • Collapse the scale responses and convert the independent variable (DIVERSITY_GOODBAD) into a binary variable
    • Rename it as DIVERSITY_GOOD
  • Code sex/gender as 1 = female, 0 = male/non-female, instead of 1s and 2s
  • Collapse the scale responses and recode political ideology as 1 = left, 2 = moderate, 3 = right
  • Classify the respondents age (straight age) into the following age groups:
    • 1 = 18 - 29, 2 = 30 - 49, 3 = 50 - 64, 4 = 65 +
  • Convert all Don't Knows andRefused to NAs
  • Select only the variables that are to be included in our model
# Create a custom function that converts the missing values in
# our measure of 1) satisfaction with democracy and 2) climate concern:

clean_response3 <- function(x) {
# Code 'Don't know' or 'Refused' as 'NA'. Else, keep it as is.
  cleaned_NA3 = ifelse(x %in% c(8, 9), NA, x)
  return(cleaned_NA3)
  }



# Clean the entire dataset:

Global.df_FINAL <- Global_edu_income_cleaned %>%
  mutate(
# Recode 'very confident' or 'somewhat confident' = 1
    CLIMATE_CONFIDENCE = ifelse(CLIMATE_INTLCOMMUNITY %in% c(1, 2), 1,
# 'not too confident' or 'not at all confident' = 0
                                ifelse(CLIMATE_INTLCOMMUNITY %in% c(3, 4), 0, NA)),
    DIVERSITY_GOOD = ifelse(DIVERSITY_GOODBAD %in% c(8, 9), NA,
# Recode 'diversity makes a better place to live' = 1
# 'diversity makes a worse place to live' or 'diversity doesn't make much difference' = 0
                            ifelse(DIVERSITY_GOODBAD == 1, 1, 0)), 
# Apply the custom function to convert NAs
    across(c(SATISFIED_DEMOCRACY, CLIMATE_CONCERN), ~ clean_response3(.x)),
    FEMALE = ifelse(SEX == 2, 1, 0), # Dummy variable for sex/gender
    AGE_CATEGORY = case_when(
        AGE == 99 ~ NA_real_,
        (AGE >= 18 & AGE <= 29) ~ 1,
        (AGE >= 30 & AGE <= 49) ~ 2,
        (AGE >= 50 & AGE <= 64) ~ 3,
         AGE >= 65 ~ 4),
    POLITICAL_ID = ifelse(POLITICAL_SCALE2 %in% c(8, 9), NA,
# Code 'extreme left' ~ 'left leaning' as 1
                          ifelse(POLITICAL_SCALE2 %in% c(0, 1, 2), 1, 
# Code 'right leaning' ~ 'extreme right' as 3; and 'center' as 2
                                 ifelse(POLITICAL_SCALE2 %in% c(4, 5, 6), 3, 2)))) %>%
  select(
    COUNTRY,
    CLIMATE_CONFIDENCE, # Dependent variable
    SATISFIED_DEMOCRACY, DIVERSITY_GOOD, # Independent variables
    CLIMATE_CONCERN, FEMALE, AGE_CATEGORY, POLITICAL_ID, EDUCATION, INCOME) # Controls


# Export the cleaned dataset
write.csv(Global.df_FINAL, file = "Global Attitudes Survey_CLEANED.csv")

b. The American Trends Panel

1) Clean the column names

US.df <- US_raw

# Remove 1) prefixes 'GAP21' and 2) suffixes '_W82' from the column names
names(US.df) <- str_remove_all(names(US_raw), "^GAP21|_W82$")

2) Code the missing values as NA

3) Standardize the responses across the Global and the US data set

  • Create a variable called COUNTRY and assign all values as US
  • To perform a logistic regression, transform the dependent variable (Q28) into a binary variable
    • Rename it as CLIMATE_CONFIDENCE
  • Convert the following variables into a binary variable:
    • Recode the independent variable (Q20) as 0s and 1s; not 1s and 2s
      • Rename Q20 as DIVERSITY_GOOD
    • Collapse the scale responses and recode sex/gender as 0s and 1s
    • Assign respondents with a BA degree to 0 and those without to 1 (for educational attainment, F_EDUCCAT)
    • Calculate the median income category of the US sample and assign those below the median to low-income (0); Otherwise, assign them to high-income (1)
    • Reverse code the U.S. measure of political ideology (F_IDEO), so that lower values represent being politically left and higher values represent being politically right
  • Select only the variables that are to be included in our model
US.df_FINAL <- US.df %>%
  mutate(
# Change all 'Refused's to NA
    across(c(starts_with("Q"), starts_with("F_")), ~ ifelse(.x == 99, NA, .x)),
# Create a new variable that indicates the nationality of the sample
    COUNTRY = 'US',
# Convert to binary variables:
    CLIMATE_CONFIDENCE = case_when(
      Q28 %in% c(1,2) ~ 1, # Code as "confident"
      Q28 %in% c(3,4) ~ 0, # as "not confident"
      TRUE ~ Q28),
# 'Diversity makes it a worse place to live' = 0; Otherwise, keep the values as-is
    DIVERSITY_GOOD = ifelse(Q20 == 2, 0, Q20),
    FEMALE = ifelse(is.na(F_GENDER), NA,
                    ifelse(F_GENDER == 2, 1, 0)), # female = 1; non-female = 0
    EDUCATION = ifelse(F_EDUCCAT %in% c(2,3), 0, F_EDUCCAT), # No BA = 0; Otherwise, keep as-is
# Distinguish between high- vs. low-income           
    INCOME = ifelse(is.na(F_INC_SDT1), NA,
                    ifelse(F_INC_SDT1 >= median(F_INC_SDT1, na.rm = TRUE), 1, 0)),
    POLITICAL_ID = case_when(
      F_IDEO %in% c(4,5) ~ 1, # Code 'Liberal' and 'Very liberal' as 'Left'
      F_IDEO == 3        ~ 2, # 'Moderate' as 'Center'
      F_IDEO %in% c(1,2) ~ 3, # 'Very conservative' and 'Conservative' as 'Right'
      TRUE ~ F_IDEO)) %>%
  rename(SATISFIED_DEMOCRACY = Q3, # Assign descriptive variable names
         CLIMATE_CONCERN     = Q24,
         AGE_CATEGORY        = F_AGECAT) %>% 
  select(COUNTRY,
         CLIMATE_CONFIDENCE, # Dependent variable
         SATISFIED_DEMOCRACY, DIVERSITY_GOOD, # Independent variables
         CLIMATE_CONCERN, FEMALE, AGE_CATEGORY, POLITICAL_ID, EDUCATION, INCOME) # Controls


# Export the cleaned dataset
write.csv(US.df_FINAL, file = "American Trends Panel_CLEANED.csv")

6) Calculate the predicted probabilities

  • For each country, compute the predicted probability that an individual would be optimistic of the impacts of global climate action, across different levels of a) diversity perception and b) satisfaction with democracy
  • Hold other (independent and control) variables constant at the median
  • In order to draw comparisons across multiple countries, set the reference point to the global median (i.e.the median of all 6 countries), NOT the national median
# Create a list of median values, which we will pass as the parameters of ggpredict()
# Set the reference to the *global* median:
median_values <- c(SATISFIED_DEMOCRACY = 2, DIVERSITY_GOOD = 1, CLIMATE_CONCERN = 2,
                   FEMALE = 0, AGE_CATEGORY = 3, POLITICAL_ID = 2, EDUCATION = 0, INCOME = 1)


# Generate predictions for each model term: 

# 1) For the Australian sample
predicted_probs_AUS <- ggpredict(model = AUS, terms = NULL, condition = median_values, pretty = TRUE)

# 2) For the Korean sample
predicted_probs_KOR <- ggpredict(model = KOR, terms = NULL, condition = median_values, pretty = TRUE)

# 3) For the German sample
predicted_probs_GER <- ggpredict(model = GER, terms = NULL, condition = median_values, pretty = TRUE)

# 4) For the Dutch sample
predicted_probs_NL <- ggpredict(model = NL, terms = NULL, condition = median_values, pretty = TRUE)

# 5) For the Swedish sample
predicted_probs_SWEDEN <- ggpredict(model = SWEDEN, terms = NULL, condition = median_values, pretty = TRUE)

# 6) For the U.S. sample
predicted_probs_USA <- ggpredict(model = USA, terms = NULL, condition = median_values, pretty = TRUE)

7) Plot the predicted probabilities

  • To allow for a cross-country comparison, create a single dataframe that summarizes the predicted probabilities of all 6 countries:
    • For each independent variable,
      1) Positive views toward social diversity and 2) Satisfaction with democracy,
    • Create a single dataframe that compiles all the
      a. predicted probabilities that an individual would be optimistic of the impacts of global climate action,
      b. their standard errors, and
      c.confidence intervals.
# 1) Create a predicted probabilities table that compares across individuals' social diversity beliefs

predicted_probs_DIVERSITY <- rbind(
  predicted_probs_AUS$DIVERSITY_GOOD, predicted_probs_KOR$DIVERSITY_GOOD,
  predicted_probs_GER$DIVERSITY_GOOD, predicted_probs_NL$DIVERSITY_GOOD,
  predicted_probs_SWEDEN$DIVERSITY_GOOD, predicted_probs_USA$DIVERSITY_GOOD) %>% 
# Add a column that indicates the country name:
# The country names should appear twice, to indicate
# the predicted probabilities when DIVERSITY_GOOD = 0 and 1, respectively
  add_column(Country = c("AUSTRALIA", "AUSTRALIA", "KOREA", "KOREA", "GERMANY", "GERMANY",
                         "THE NETHERLANDS", "THE NETHERLANDS", "SWEDEN", "SWEDEN", "USA", "USA"), .before = "x") %>%
# Give a descriptive label to the 'x' column, which indicates different levels of social diversity beliefs:
  rename(DIVERSITY_GOOD = x) %>%
# Remove the 'group' column, as it indicates redundant variable names (= DIVERSITY_GOOD):
  select(-group)


# 2) Create a predicted probabilities table that compares across different levels of satisfaction with democracy

predicted_probs_DEMOCRACY <- rbind(
  predicted_probs_AUS$SATISFIED_DEMOCRACY, predicted_probs_KOR$SATISFIED_DEMOCRACY,
  predicted_probs_GER$SATISFIED_DEMOCRACY, predicted_probs_NL$SATISFIED_DEMOCRACY,
  predicted_probs_SWEDEN$SATISFIED_DEMOCRACY,
  predicted_probs_USA$SATISFIED_DEMOCRACY) %>% 
# The country names should appear 4 times, to indicate
# the predicted probabilities when SATISFIED_DEMOCRACY = 1, 2, 3, 4
  add_column(Country = c("AUSTRALIA", "AUSTRALIA", "AUSTRALIA","AUSTRALIA",
                         "KOREA", "KOREA", "KOREA", "KOREA",
                         "GERMANY", "GERMANY","GERMANY", "GERMANY",
                         "THE NETHERLANDS", "THE NETHERLANDS","THE NETHERLANDS", "THE NETHERLANDS",
                         "SWEDEN", "SWEDEN","SWEDEN", "SWEDEN",
                         "USA", "USA", "USA", "USA"), .before = "x") %>%
# Give a descriptive label to the 'x' column, which refers to different levels of satisfaction with democracy:
  rename(SATISFIED_DEMOCRACY = x) %>%
  select(-group)
  • Plot the predicted probabilities and confidence intervals for each independent variable and for each country
# Generate a scatterplot with error bars extending from both sides 
predicted_probs_DIVERSITY %>% ggplot(
  aes(x = factor(DIVERSITY_GOOD), y = predicted, color = Country)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymax = conf.high, ymin = conf.low), alpha = 0.25, width = 0.5, color = "black") +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 1), n.breaks = 6) +
  scale_color_discrete(breaks = c(0:5),
                       labels = c("AUSTRALIA", "KOREA", "GERMANY", "THE NETHERLANDS", "SWEDEN","USA")) +
  labs(title = "The predicted probabilities of the level of confidence \n in our ability to tackle global climate change", 
       x = "Diversity makes the world a better place", 
       y = "Predicted probability", 
       subtitle = "A cross-country comparison along diversity perceptions", 
       caption = "Source: The Pew Research Center. \n Note: Bars represent 95% Confidence Intervals.
       The graph shows the predicted probabilities while holding all other values constant at their median.") +
  theme(plot.title =  element_text(hjust = 0.5, face = "bold"), 
        plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
        plot.caption = element_text(hjust = 1, size = 9),
        text = element_text(size = 10.5)) +
  facet_wrap(~ Country, nrow = 1)
